Preheat your oven to 200°C. Chop the @sweet potato{1} into 1cm chunks (no need to peel!). Halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1}. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Pop the sweet potato onto a #baking tray{} with a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} and season with @salt and @pepper. Toss to coat, then spread out in an even layer and roast on the top shelf of your oven until golden and soft, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a large #frying pan{} over medium high heat. Once hot, add the @Linda McCartney Vegetarian Meatballs{8}. Fry, turning regularly, until browned and crispy, ~{4-5%minutes}. Transfer to a #plate{} but don't wash up the pan! Add half of the red onion and cook until softened, ~{8-10%minutes}. Whilst the onion cooks, roughly chop the @coriander{1}(roughly chopped) (stalks and all).

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a medium #saucepan{} over medium high heat. Add the remaining onion and season with salt. Cook, stirring regularly, until softened, ~{8-10%minutes}. Pour the @water for the couscous{240%ml} into the saucepan and bring to the boil. When boiling, stir in the @couscous{120%g}, pop a lid on the pan and remove from the heat. Leave to the side for ~{8-10%minutes} or until ready to serve.

Meanwhile, add the garlic and @harissa paste{50%g} to frying pan with the onion. Cook, stirring, for ~{1%minute}, then add the @finely chopped tomatoes{1}(finely chopped), @water for the sauce{50%ml} and a pinch of @sugar{pinch}. Season with salt and pepper. Simmer for ~{8-10%minutes} then return the meatballs to the pan. Simmer until thick and tomatoey, a further ~{5%minutes}.

Do any washing up whilst you wait. Once the couscous is cooked, carefully fluff up with a #fork{}. Taste and add more salt and pepper if you like.

Stir the roasted sweet potato and half the coriander through the tagine and add a splash of water if you need to. Taste and add salt and pepper if needed. Divide the couscous between plates, spoon over the tagine then top with the @low fat natural yoghurt{75%g} and remaining coriander. Enjoy!

> This warming and hearty Vegetarian Meatball Tagine is bursting full of flavours and makes the perfect dinner night option.